      <!-- Buyer's guide -->
      <article class="legal-prose mt-16">
        <h2>What to look for in an IPTV box UK 2026</h2>
        <p>
          If you are new to IPTV, the specs above can look like alphabet soup. Here are the five
          things that actually matter when you shortlist a box for a UK household:
        </p>

        <h3>1. Portal / Xtream Codes support</h3>
        <p>
          Most UK IPTV subscriptions today are delivered via Xtream Codes API (username, password,
          server URL) or a Stalker portal (MAC address). Boxes that ship with a proper portal loader —
          <em>Formuler, BuzzTV, MAG</em> — save you sideloading apps. If you buy a Fire Stick or Shield,
          you will install IPTV Smarters Pro or TiviMate manually. Neither is hard, but a portal box is
          the "put it under the telly and forget it" option.
        </p>

        <h3>2. 4K HDR handling</h3>
        <p>
          Any box you buy in 2026 should support 4K HDR10 at 60 fps. Dolby Vision is nice-to-have but
          rarely available on IPTV feeds today. Watch out for cheap Android boxes that <em>claim</em> 4K
          but drop back to 1080p under real load.
        </p>

        <h3>3. Storage and RAM</h3>
        <p>
          2 GB RAM is the minimum for a smooth EPG. 4 GB is the sweet spot for TiviMate + multi-view.
          Storage matters less because IPTV apps are small — but 8 GB minimum, otherwise updates fail.
        </p>

        <h3>4. Ethernet, not just Wi-Fi</h3>
        <p>
          The single biggest cause of "IPTV keeps buffering" complaints is Wi-Fi. Every box in our top
          five has Gigabit or 100 Mbps Ethernet — use it. If you cannot run a cable, get a Wi-Fi 6 box
          and put it in the same room as the router.
        </p>

        <h3>5. Long-term software support</h3>
        <p>
          IPTV apps evolve fast. A box that stops getting Android updates 12 months after you buy it
          will eventually stop supporting the latest IPTV Smarters release. Formuler, Nvidia and Amazon
          have the best track records; no-name Android boxes are a false economy.
        </p>

        <h2>Try an IPTV trial before you spend on a box</h2>
        <p>
          The single best piece of advice we give buyers is this: <strong>test the service first, buy
          the box second</strong>. Any of the boxes above can cost £70 to £250, but you can prove that
          our channel line-up, 4K picture and EPG are what you want for £{site.price} on our
          <a href="/" class="text-brand-light underline underline-offset-4 decoration-brand/40 hover:decoration-brand-light">30-day IPTV trial UK</a>. Install IPTV Smarters on a phone, a laptop or the
          Fire Stick you already own — if you are happy after a few days, then invest in a dedicated
          Formuler or BuzzTV. It is the cheapest way to protect yourself from buying the wrong hardware.
        </p>

        <h2>Best IPTV app for each box</h2>
        <p>
          Hardware is only half the story — the app you run on top defines the experience. Here is our
          quick-fire recommendation per box:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Formuler Z11 Pro Max:</strong> MYTVOnline 3 (built-in) — nothing beats it for portals.</li>
          <li><strong>Fire TV Stick 4K Max:</strong> IPTV Smarters Pro — sideload via the Downloader app.</li>
          <li><strong>Nvidia Shield TV Pro:</strong> TiviMate (premium unlock is worth it).</li>
          <li><strong>BuzzTV XR4500:</strong> BuzzTV Essentials or IPTV Smarters Pro.</li>
          <li><strong>MAG 524w3:</strong> the built-in Infomir portal — no app needed.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          If you want a step-by-step walkthrough for any of these, our
          <a href="/installation-guides/">installation guides</a> cover every popular device in the UK.
        </p>

        <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
      </article>

